on how to study philosophy?

01:55:37.880 --> 01:55:40.440
And secondly, what advice would you have

01:55:40.440 --> 01:55:42.760
on writing philosophy?

01:55:45.840 --> 01:55:48.840
So as far as studying philosophy goes,

01:55:50.040 --> 01:55:52.880
it's always a good idea to have an understanding

01:55:52.880 --> 01:55:56.120
of the history of philosophy.

01:55:56.120 --> 01:56:00.560
That way, you kind of, so getting an idea of the history,

01:56:00.760 --> 01:56:04.840
if you reflect on that sort of study,

01:56:04.840 --> 01:56:09.040
you start to come to certain realizations

01:56:09.040 --> 01:56:14.040
as far as maybe how one idea inspired another idea.

01:56:16.520 --> 01:56:21.520
And you also get an idea of what's been said already.

01:56:22.840 --> 01:56:25.840
So, okay, so when you get into philosophy,

01:56:25.840 --> 01:56:27.120
sometimes it happens where you think

01:56:27.120 --> 01:56:29.120
you have a really cool novel idea

01:56:29.120 --> 01:56:30.000
based on something you've read,

01:56:30.800 --> 01:56:33.000
but then you realize that somebody else also said that

01:56:33.000 --> 01:56:34.440
like a thousand years ago.

01:56:34.440 --> 01:56:37.880
And so, the thing of the history is good for that reason too.

01:56:37.880 --> 01:56:41.600
So you're not just spending time reiterating something

01:56:41.600 --> 01:56:44.440
that somebody's already done a thousand or 2,000 years ago.

01:56:45.400 --> 01:56:50.120
It also gives you an idea that nothing is absolute

01:56:50.120 --> 01:56:55.120
in the sense that, I mean, you can see how much has changed

01:56:55.600 --> 01:56:59.800
over the centuries of philosophical thought

01:56:59.800 --> 01:57:04.800
and I think that's good for the ego,

01:57:05.040 --> 01:57:06.840
just to get a given understanding

01:57:06.840 --> 01:57:10.120
that they didn't have the absolute truth.

01:57:10.120 --> 01:57:11.800
I'm not gonna get the absolute truth,

01:57:11.800 --> 01:57:13.160
but we can think about these things

01:57:13.160 --> 01:57:16.680
and still maybe discern partial truths

01:57:16.680 --> 01:57:18.760
or something like that.

01:57:19.760 --> 01:57:21.200
I always like to have that in mind

01:57:21.200 --> 01:57:23.880
when I'm writing things or thinking about things.

01:57:24.880 --> 01:57:28.400
So any more, like when it comes to your process

01:57:28.400 --> 01:57:31.040
of reading, writing, what's the,

01:57:31.040 --> 01:57:33.600
how does it look like on a day-to-day basis?

01:57:34.960 --> 01:57:39.960
Consistency is, I think, what has helped me above all else.

01:57:41.440 --> 01:57:43.120
Like just reading a little bit every day

01:57:43.120 --> 01:57:45.280
or studying a little bit every day when you can't,

01:57:45.280 --> 01:57:46.720
like even if it's 20 minutes.

01:57:46.720 --> 01:57:48.240
So like the first thing,

01:57:48.240 --> 01:57:50.040
a lot of times the first thing I do in the morning

01:57:50.680 --> 01:57:55.680
is I listen to a lecture or I listen to part of an audio book

01:57:56.280 --> 01:58:00.120
or a podcast, you know, where they're discussing certain things.

01:58:01.440 --> 01:58:03.720
Because that just really gets my mind going right away

01:58:03.720 --> 01:58:05.520
as far as thinking about these things.

01:58:07.120 --> 01:58:10.440
And the reason why I choose, sometimes I'm too tired,

01:58:10.440 --> 01:58:11.760
like for the first hour that I wake up

01:58:11.760 --> 01:58:13.320
that I can't really force myself to read,

01:58:13.320 --> 01:58:15.320
but I can listen to something.

01:58:15.320 --> 01:58:16.760
I can get my coffee.

01:58:16.760 --> 01:58:18.520
Yeah, yeah, yeah, you can,

01:58:18.520 --> 01:58:19.960
I can listen and drink coffee.

01:58:19.960 --> 01:58:22.200
It's hard for me to read and make my coffee.

01:58:24.320 --> 01:58:27.480
So I think repetition or consistency

01:58:27.480 --> 01:58:30.600
and just persevering, like you think you don't understand

01:58:30.600 --> 01:58:32.920
some of the things, like don't just stop reading it,

01:58:32.920 --> 01:58:34.080
just read it.

01:58:34.080 --> 01:58:35.680
Even if you don't understand it, just read it

01:58:35.680 --> 01:58:39.280
because you might start to understand

01:58:39.280 --> 01:58:42.240
bits of it after you're finished.

01:58:42.240 --> 01:58:43.520
And even if you don't,

01:58:43.520 --> 01:58:45.800
things might start to make sense maybe months later

01:58:45.800 --> 01:58:47.080
or something like that.

01:58:47.080 --> 01:58:49.440
That's the experience I had with high degree in time.

01:58:49.440 --> 01:58:52.120
I read it once and came away from it saying,

01:58:52.120 --> 01:58:55.560
dude, I don't understand literally anything this guy said.

01:58:57.240 --> 01:58:59.440
But I feel like there's something really important here.

01:58:59.440 --> 01:59:03.600
And so I really dove into secondary sources and lectures

01:59:03.600 --> 01:59:06.200
and going through the book multiple times after that.

01:59:07.400 --> 01:59:10.960
And so I would say just read a little bit every day

01:59:10.960 --> 01:59:14.520
and make notes right in the margins of your book.

01:59:14.520 --> 01:59:15.760
If you have a physical book,

01:59:15.760 --> 01:59:18.960
don't try to keep your book super perfect and neat.

01:59:18.960 --> 01:59:22.840
Just start writing stuff down and highlighting stuff.

01:59:22.840 --> 01:59:25.560
If you have a question about something you read

01:59:25.560 --> 01:59:27.080
and it seems like it's a good question,

01:59:27.080 --> 01:59:29.680
write the question next to the paragraph in the book.

01:59:29.680 --> 01:59:32.440
I just doing small things like that

01:59:32.440 --> 01:59:34.320
has helped me a whole lot.

01:59:34.320 --> 01:59:36.600
Highlighting things you think are important.

01:59:36.600 --> 01:59:38.120
And then highlighting things in a different color

01:59:38.120 --> 01:59:39.840
that you just don't understand.

01:59:39.840 --> 01:59:41.960
You know, because you can go back through

01:59:42.040 --> 01:59:46.400
and you can, it has to be an active process, I guess.

01:59:46.400 --> 01:59:48.640
Maybe that's what I'm trying to get around to.

01:59:48.640 --> 01:59:50.640
It involves an active process.

01:59:50.640 --> 01:59:53.360
You're not just sitting there and taking in words

01:59:53.360 --> 01:59:55.440
that you're seeing with your eyes.

01:59:55.440 --> 01:59:58.360
It's an involved process of writing

01:59:58.360 --> 02:00:00.280
and thinking and reflecting.

02:00:00.280 --> 02:00:03.760
And don't be concerned with reading too quickly

02:00:03.760 --> 02:00:06.760
or saying, it's taking me forever to get to the 10 pages,

02:00:06.760 --> 02:00:10.560
but it's gonna take me a year to read being in time.

02:00:12.160 --> 02:00:13.520
Just give it the time.

02:00:13.520 --> 02:00:15.800
It will be quicker and easier to read.

02:00:15.800 --> 02:00:18.120
And I just like to take the approach

02:00:18.120 --> 02:00:19.960
of giving things the time that they ask.

02:00:19.960 --> 02:00:22.200
They're gonna ask you for a certain amount of time

02:00:22.200 --> 02:00:24.320
and just give it to them.

02:00:26.560 --> 02:00:30.200
So do you normally pick a thinker

02:00:30.200 --> 02:00:32.720
and then study all of that thinker's work,

02:00:32.720 --> 02:00:36.720
the whole over of the thinker's work?

02:00:36.720 --> 02:00:40.440
Or do you rather pick, let's say,

02:00:40.440 --> 02:00:44.320
a fundamental philosophical text

02:00:44.320 --> 02:00:47.080
like it could be critique of pure reason

02:00:47.080 --> 02:00:50.480
or some of Plato's Republic, whatever it may be,

02:00:50.480 --> 02:00:53.320
and then focus on the text itself?

02:00:53.320 --> 02:00:55.960
Or are you more thinker focused?

02:00:59.400 --> 02:01:04.400
So really, I'm more thinker focused now

02:01:05.760 --> 02:01:09.240
than I have ever been, but previous to this,

02:01:09.240 --> 02:01:14.240
I almost always say I was thinking just broadly.

02:01:14.920 --> 02:01:17.360
Let's just say I was thinking about topics

02:01:17.360 --> 02:01:18.640
and philosophy of mine.

02:01:21.280 --> 02:01:26.280
And maybe I got intrigued by physicalism.

02:01:28.000 --> 02:01:31.680
Well, then I would go through and I would try to find

02:01:31.680 --> 02:01:33.120
what the history of physicalism was

02:01:33.120 --> 02:01:38.000
and what the major thinkers were in kind of read along

02:01:38.000 --> 02:01:42.640
the concept or the theory from a variety of perspectives.

02:01:42.640 --> 02:01:45.600
And then I really immerse myself in it

02:01:45.600 --> 02:01:49.320
and try to think from that perspective.

02:01:49.320 --> 02:01:51.560
And sometimes you do have to spend a lot of time

02:01:51.560 --> 02:01:54.400
to get to the added areas

02:01:54.400 --> 02:01:57.320
or to get attuned to that kind of motive thought

02:01:57.320 --> 02:02:00.000
so that you have to spend more time.

02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:03.960
But then after that, I would read the opposite view.

02:02:03.960 --> 02:02:06.400
Whatever the opposite view was,

02:02:06.440 --> 02:02:08.560
not necessarily just arguments against

02:02:08.560 --> 02:02:09.800
whatever position it is,

02:02:09.800 --> 02:02:13.880
but what's like a contrasting theory or idea.

02:02:13.880 --> 02:02:15.000
And then I would dive into that.

02:02:15.000 --> 02:02:15.840
And so I did that.

02:02:15.840 --> 02:02:20.400
Honestly, that's what most of my undergrad time doing

02:02:20.400 --> 02:02:25.400
was just like kind of juxtaposing theories and concepts

02:02:25.800 --> 02:02:27.600
with contrasting theories.

02:02:28.560 --> 02:02:30.440
And just trying to get a really holistic view

02:02:30.440 --> 02:02:32.000
of like why people think things.

02:02:32.840 --> 02:02:36.640
I don't have very strong opinions personally.

02:02:37.560 --> 02:02:40.200
It's easier for me to do that sort of study.

02:02:40.200 --> 02:02:43.800
I'm just, I'm always very skeptical of everything,

02:02:43.800 --> 02:02:46.600
but also myself at the same time and try to say,

02:02:46.600 --> 02:02:49.520
I mean, I can appreciate ideas that maybe I disagree with.

02:02:52.040 --> 02:02:57.040
And it'd be very difficult to say anything absolutely.

02:02:58.360 --> 02:02:59.200
I could-

02:02:59.800 --> 02:03:01.040
Well, it's interesting though,

02:03:01.040 --> 02:03:06.040
I hear a typical trope by more public intellectuals

02:03:06.880 --> 02:03:11.400
is be skeptical, be open-minded, be critical,

02:03:11.400 --> 02:03:12.880
be objective, be rational,

02:03:12.880 --> 02:03:16.800
we hear all these terms thrown around quite a lot, isn't it?

02:03:16.800 --> 02:03:20.600
But it's also sometimes I think,

02:03:20.600 --> 02:03:25.200
I'm not trying to pick on a particular public intellectual,

02:03:25.200 --> 02:03:27.560
like someone like Steven Pinko or Sam Harris

02:03:27.560 --> 02:03:31.320
who constantly to almost like ad nauseam,

02:03:31.320 --> 02:03:33.880
talk about rationality and reason

02:03:33.880 --> 02:03:35.960
and being open-minded and whatnot.

02:03:37.880 --> 02:03:41.360
They also don't seem to get it that in fact, firstly,

02:03:41.360 --> 02:03:45.200
being skeptical, being critical is,

02:03:45.200 --> 02:03:47.040
it's a really difficult thing to do.

02:03:47.040 --> 02:03:50.840
It's in fact quite unnerving.

02:03:50.840 --> 02:03:53.480
It leaves one in this state of angst

02:03:53.480 --> 02:03:55.560
and there's no stability in one's life.

02:03:56.560 --> 02:04:00.120
